00:00:23.070 --> 00:00:24.710
PROFESSOR: Today we're
going to continue

00:00:24.710 --> 00:00:28.180
discussing firm behavior.

00:00:28.180 --> 00:00:32.830
But today we're going to deviate
from our fantasy land

00:00:32.830 --> 00:00:36.580
of 14.01 to come to the real
world a little bit which is to

00:00:36.580 --> 00:00:41.840
talk a bit about whether firms
actually maximize profits.

00:00:41.840 --> 00:00:48.190
The whole presumption of
producer theory is just as we

00:00:48.190 --> 00:00:51.130
think with consumer theory,
consumers maximize utility.

00:00:51.130 --> 00:00:53.570
Except producers maximize
profits.

00:00:53.570 --> 00:00:56.190
That turns out to be an
incredibly useful shorthand

00:00:56.190 --> 00:00:57.780
for lots of things.

00:00:57.780 --> 00:01:00.470
And it will turn out to be,
as with any simplifying

00:01:00.470 --> 00:01:05.519
assumption, largely right and
largely will help us draw a

00:01:05.519 --> 00:01:08.320
lot of interesting conclusions
about firms and markets.

00:01:08.320 --> 00:01:11.550
Nonetheless, it's clearly
not right in

00:01:11.550 --> 00:01:14.110
reality for every firm.

00:01:14.110 --> 00:01:18.240
For example, we see lots of
firms doing things which look

00:01:18.240 --> 00:01:20.940
pretty wasteful like big
corporate jets or

00:01:20.940 --> 00:01:22.760
other things like that.

00:01:22.760 --> 00:01:26.780
More relevantly, huge pay for
CEOs seems pretty wasteful.

00:01:26.780 --> 00:01:30.920
So, for example, on 2004 the net
income of Eli Lilly, the

00:01:30.920 --> 00:01:33.800
drug manufacturer,
fell by 29%.

00:01:33.800 --> 00:01:38.940
Yet the CEO got a 41% raise to
to $12.5 million a year.

00:01:38.940 --> 00:01:42.040
Or even more so in the financial
crisis, in 2009,

00:01:42.040 --> 00:01:45.285
Citigroup and Merrill each lost
more than $27 billion.

00:01:45.285 --> 00:01:46.830
It's a pretty bad year
for the financial

00:01:46.830 --> 00:01:48.390
sector, you might think.

00:01:48.390 --> 00:01:52.290
And yet their CEO's pay in each
company rose by more than

00:01:52.290 --> 00:01:54.650
10% to about $15 million.

00:01:54.650 --> 00:01:59.380
So in the worst year for the
financial system since 1929,

00:01:59.380 --> 00:02:02.350
the CEO pay increased in
these two companies.

00:02:02.350 --> 00:02:05.610
So you might think that this
sounds kind of off.

00:02:05.610 --> 00:02:06.630
How could we explain that?

00:02:06.630 --> 00:02:08.789
Well, there's two possible
explanations.

00:02:08.789 --> 00:02:10.990
So one explanation is that
things which look wasteful

00:02:10.990 --> 00:02:12.280
really aren't.

00:02:12.280 --> 00:02:14.510
That is that we pay CEOs a
huge amount of money, but

00:02:14.510 --> 00:02:16.070
they're worth it.

00:02:16.070 --> 00:02:20.450
So, for example, even at his
ultimate salary of $33 million

00:02:20.450 --> 00:02:23.600
per year, Michael Jordan
was vastly underpaid.

00:02:23.600 --> 00:02:25.920
By any reasonable economic
analysis of the value he added

00:02:25.920 --> 00:02:29.410
to the Chicago Bulls, it was
well in excess of $50 million.

00:02:29.410 --> 00:02:31.380
So even though he was
paid $33 million,

00:02:31.380 --> 00:02:34.020
Michael Jordan was underpaid.

00:02:34.020 --> 00:02:35.860
Similarly, just because someone
gets paid a lot of

00:02:35.860 --> 00:02:37.830
money, doesn't mean that
they're overpaid.

00:02:37.830 --> 00:02:39.840
These CEOs are very
talented people.

00:02:39.840 --> 00:02:41.090
They may be underpaid.

00:02:41.090 --> 00:02:43.750
Now this is an argument you
might have made with a

00:02:43.750 --> 00:02:45.930
somewhat straight face maybe
10 or 15 years ago.

00:02:45.930 --> 00:02:47.890
It's hard to make that with
a straight face now.

00:02:47.890 --> 00:02:51.150
It's hard to believe that these
CEOs of these companies

00:02:51.150 --> 00:02:53.500
aren't overpaid given their
company performance and even

00:02:53.500 --> 00:02:56.340
the kind of facts we
just talked about.

00:02:56.340 --> 00:03:00.150
So a better explanation for
things like excessive CEO pay

00:03:00.150 --> 00:03:04.340
is something which we call
the agency problem.

00:03:13.280 --> 00:03:16.520
And that's what I want to
emphasize in today's lecture.

00:03:16.520 --> 00:03:22.000
In reality, we think of a firm
as something where there's a

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:23.710
guy who's an owner.

00:03:23.710 --> 00:03:25.340
He hires some machines
and some workers.

00:03:25.340 --> 00:03:29.110
They make stuff that he thought
of, and you produce

00:03:29.110 --> 00:03:31.270
it, and some profit is made.

00:03:31.270 --> 00:03:34.110
So the model we have in mind
when we talked about the firms

00:03:34.110 --> 00:03:37.720
so far in this course is the
model of what we might call a

00:03:37.720 --> 00:03:40.890
sole proprietorship
or a partnership.

00:03:40.890 --> 00:03:43.830
It's a model where one
individual, where there's

00:03:43.830 --> 00:03:45.640
basically a commonality.

00:03:45.640 --> 00:03:47.370
The key thing that we've
discussed so far is a

00:03:47.370 --> 00:03:52.240
commonality of interest between
the owners who own the

00:03:52.240 --> 00:03:56.740
company and the control
of production.

00:03:56.740 --> 00:03:59.710
So the people who earn the money
from the company also

00:03:59.710 --> 00:04:01.210
control the production.

00:04:01.210 --> 00:04:04.310
So when you start your start-ups
when you graduate,

00:04:04.310 --> 00:04:06.370
you will start them as a sole
proprietorship or a

00:04:06.370 --> 00:04:09.870
partnership where you own the
company, and you control

00:04:09.870 --> 00:04:11.410
what's done.

00:04:11.410 --> 00:04:14.815
You're there 18 hours a day
making sure the guys are doing

00:04:14.815 --> 00:04:16.570
what they're supposed to do.

00:04:16.570 --> 00:04:19.110
And you're who gets the money
if they succeed or lose the

00:04:19.110 --> 00:04:21.070
money if they fail.

00:04:21.070 --> 00:04:24.120
And that's the model we've had
in mind as we've thought about

00:04:24.120 --> 00:04:27.610
corporations or firms
so far in our class.

00:04:27.610 --> 00:04:30.230
But, in fact, most production
in the US

00:04:30.230 --> 00:04:32.260
doesn't happen that way.

00:04:32.260 --> 00:04:35.450
Most production in the US
happens through the guise of

00:04:35.450 --> 00:04:36.700
corporations.

00:04:41.710 --> 00:04:46.790
Corporations are marked
by a separation of

00:04:46.790 --> 00:04:48.600
ownership and control.

00:04:48.600 --> 00:04:52.140
What defines a corporation
is a separation of

00:04:52.140 --> 00:04:54.240
ownership and control.

00:04:54.240 --> 00:04:57.800
The owners of corporations are
the stockholders or what we

00:04:57.800 --> 00:05:02.350
call the equity holders, people
who have invested money

00:05:02.350 --> 00:05:03.850
in the corporation.

00:05:03.850 --> 00:05:05.930
So the owners of the corporation
are its investors,

00:05:05.930 --> 00:05:07.380
its stockholders, its
equity holders.

00:05:09.940 --> 00:05:13.460
All of you, most of you,
probably somewhere--

00:05:13.460 --> 00:05:16.050
if you're Jewish, it's in some
Bar Mitzvah gift you got, if

00:05:16.050 --> 00:05:18.250
you're not, it's in some other
gift you got-- probably have

00:05:18.250 --> 00:05:21.570
some equity ownership in
something somewhere.

00:05:21.570 --> 00:05:22.230
OK.

00:05:22.230 --> 00:05:24.360
You maybe have a little bond
which says you own five shares

00:05:24.360 --> 00:05:25.830
of GM that someone gave you,
because they thought it'd be

00:05:25.830 --> 00:05:27.420
cute or whatever.

00:05:27.420 --> 00:05:29.260
That's now worthless, but maybe
some other company.

00:05:31.810 --> 00:05:32.590
We're equity holders.

00:05:32.590 --> 00:05:35.420
We invest in companies.

00:05:35.420 --> 00:05:38.110
But we don't make the
production decision.

00:05:38.110 --> 00:05:40.670
The production decision is made
by the firm's managers

00:05:40.670 --> 00:05:47.230
who are employees of the owners,
the equity holders.

00:05:47.230 --> 00:05:48.910
Now these managers may
have some ownership.

00:05:48.910 --> 00:05:50.430
And we'll talk about that
in a little bit.

00:05:50.430 --> 00:05:54.090
But, by and large, the primary
ownership of the firm is done

00:05:54.090 --> 00:05:56.370
by people who do not control
the everyday decisions of

00:05:56.370 --> 00:05:56.990
production.

00:05:56.990 --> 00:05:59.260
And it sort of makes sense
it has to be that way.

00:05:59.260 --> 00:06:02.830
When a company's as big
as Microsoft, you

00:06:02.830 --> 00:06:04.190
couldn't have me.

00:06:04.190 --> 00:06:07.570
Somewhere, I'm sure if you add
up my various stock funds I

00:06:07.570 --> 00:06:12.830
own, I own 0.000000000001%
of Microsoft.

00:06:12.830 --> 00:06:15.500
It'd be crazy to have
me involved with a

00:06:15.500 --> 00:06:18.800
0.000000000001% of the
decision making.

00:06:18.800 --> 00:06:21.620
I don't know anything about
anything that Microsoft does.

00:06:21.620 --> 00:06:23.640
It makes sense that there's a
separation of ownership and

00:06:23.640 --> 00:06:26.330
control once companies
get big enough.

00:06:26.330 --> 00:06:29.240
But the fact that there is a
separation of ownership and

00:06:29.240 --> 00:06:32.630
control can lead to this agency
problem and can lead to

00:06:32.630 --> 00:06:36.690
firms not maximizing profits.

00:06:36.690 --> 00:06:42.220
So, basically, the point is that
managers care not just

00:06:42.220 --> 00:06:44.320
about the profits they
make but also how

00:06:44.320 --> 00:06:46.310
happy their life is.

00:06:46.310 --> 00:06:49.220
And things which make their life
happy may be things which

00:06:49.220 --> 00:06:51.530
aren't profit maximizing.

00:06:51.530 --> 00:06:54.850
The managers who are in charge
of production may have their

00:06:54.850 --> 00:06:59.410
own agenda that deviates from
profit maximization.

00:06:59.410 --> 00:07:02.630
And the problem is it may be
hard to figure that out if

00:07:02.630 --> 00:07:04.950
you're the owner of the firm.

00:07:04.950 --> 00:07:08.200
So the agency problem is the
first example of a problem

00:07:08.200 --> 00:07:11.090
we'll talk about later in the
semester of imperfect

00:07:11.090 --> 00:07:12.680
information.

00:07:12.680 --> 00:07:18.610
This is the first time we'll
see imperfect information.

00:07:18.610 --> 00:07:22.160
We've assumed in our class so
far, and we'll assume in our

00:07:22.160 --> 00:07:24.780
class going forward that there's
perfect information

00:07:24.780 --> 00:07:27.380
the world, that everyone knows
what stuff costs, that

00:07:27.380 --> 00:07:30.540
everyone can shop costlessly
across providers, et cetera.

00:07:30.540 --> 00:07:32.800
But, in fact, the world
is marked by imperfect

00:07:32.800 --> 00:07:34.780
information.

00:07:34.780 --> 00:07:39.070
As an owner of Microsoft, as a
trivial owner of Microsoft, I

00:07:39.070 --> 00:07:41.960
don't know for sure that every
Microsoft employee is doing

00:07:41.960 --> 00:07:43.630
what's profit maximizing
for the company.

00:07:43.630 --> 00:07:45.150
I can't.

00:07:45.150 --> 00:07:46.650
It's just impossible
for me to own that.

00:07:46.650 --> 00:07:49.050
So that creates an
agency problem.

00:07:49.050 --> 00:07:52.340
And the agency problem arises
because it's in the employees'

00:07:52.340 --> 00:07:53.970
interest, perhaps, to do things
which aren't profit

00:07:53.970 --> 00:07:54.590
maximizing.

00:07:54.590 --> 00:07:58.130
So so as a simple example,
imagine that you're an

00:07:58.130 --> 00:08:01.120
investor in the company that's
a medium-sized company.

00:08:01.120 --> 00:08:03.910
And the head of that company is
jealous because all of his

00:08:03.910 --> 00:08:05.840
friends at bigger companies have
their own jets, and he's

00:08:05.840 --> 00:08:07.610
got to fly commercial.

00:08:07.610 --> 00:08:12.375
He says, I want my own jet,
because I'm not cool enough.

00:08:12.375 --> 00:08:16.370
There's this great episode of
the Simpsons where Burns goes

00:08:16.370 --> 00:08:17.940
to the billionaires club.

00:08:17.940 --> 00:08:19.130
And he's in the billionaires
club.

00:08:19.130 --> 00:08:21.136
And then eventually his wealth
drops so low he gets thrown

00:08:21.136 --> 00:08:23.020
into the millionaires club, and
it's these yokels in the

00:08:23.020 --> 00:08:23.580
millionaires club.

00:08:23.580 --> 00:08:25.970
He's like, I want to be back
in the billionaires club.

00:08:25.970 --> 00:08:29.980
The point is managers of
companies care about how they

00:08:29.980 --> 00:08:31.300
look and who they
hang out with.

00:08:31.300 --> 00:08:33.090
And you've got this manager of
a medium-sized company who

00:08:33.090 --> 00:08:33.909
wants his own private jet.

00:08:33.909 --> 00:08:36.820
But he knows that that's
not profit maximizing.

00:08:36.820 --> 00:08:39.460
Because he knows that if he
figures out his travel, and

00:08:39.460 --> 00:08:41.905
prices it out at competitive
prices, it'll be cheaper to

00:08:41.905 --> 00:08:43.270
just travel commercial.

00:08:43.270 --> 00:08:43.900
So what does he do?

00:08:43.900 --> 00:08:48.270
He puts together a glossy
PowerPoint which he presents

00:08:48.270 --> 00:08:51.060
to you, the owner of the
company, showing that

00:08:51.060 --> 00:08:54.780
financially it would be more
prudent to own a jet than to

00:08:54.780 --> 00:08:56.005
fly commercial.

00:08:56.005 --> 00:08:58.186
What he doesn't point out and
put into that PowerPoint is

00:08:58.186 --> 00:09:00.270
that in putting together the
commercial prices he used, he

00:09:00.270 --> 00:09:02.820
chose the highest rates from
flying from point A to point

00:09:02.820 --> 00:09:04.990
B, not the lowest rates.

00:09:04.990 --> 00:09:06.656
Now, unless you're an expert
on the cost of flying from

00:09:06.656 --> 00:09:08.010
point A to point B, you
won't know that.

00:09:08.010 --> 00:09:09.110
You'll say, well, that's
a pretty impressive

00:09:09.110 --> 00:09:09.650
presentation.

00:09:09.650 --> 00:09:12.640
Yes, you can show you've saved
20% by having your own plane.

00:09:12.640 --> 00:09:13.630
Go get it.

00:09:13.630 --> 00:09:15.640
But it turned out he
didn't save 20%.

00:09:15.640 --> 00:09:18.050
He just cooked the numbers in
a way to make his life nicer

00:09:18.050 --> 00:09:20.300
even if it wasn't profit
maximizing.

00:09:20.300 --> 00:09:23.170
And that's an example of the
kind of problem that arises

00:09:23.170 --> 00:09:24.420
with imperfect information.

00:09:27.420 --> 00:09:29.070
And I could go through examples
all the time.

00:09:29.070 --> 00:09:31.470
But I think you guys probably
all understand what I'm

00:09:31.470 --> 00:09:33.930
talking about, which is there's
lots of ways employees

00:09:33.930 --> 00:09:36.290
of companies might make their
lives nicer that aren't profit

00:09:36.290 --> 00:09:37.300
maximizing.

00:09:37.300 --> 00:09:39.450
Now, corporations have
recognized this from time

00:09:39.450 --> 00:09:41.010
immemorial.

00:09:41.010 --> 00:09:43.080
And they've recognized that
their owners are too diffuse

00:09:43.080 --> 00:09:43.730
to monitor this.

00:09:43.730 --> 00:09:46.350
So what corporations do
is they have set up an

00:09:46.350 --> 00:09:52.430
intermediary between the owners
and the producers

00:09:52.430 --> 00:09:53.680
called the board of directors.

00:09:58.710 --> 00:10:01.570
The board of directors is a set
of individuals appointed

00:10:01.570 --> 00:10:04.320
by the owners that are supposed
to actually pay

00:10:04.320 --> 00:10:07.040
attention to what's going
on in production.

00:10:07.040 --> 00:10:09.470
The owners say, look, we can't
afford to pay attention.

00:10:09.470 --> 00:10:11.350
But we're going to appoint you,
the board of directors,

00:10:11.350 --> 00:10:12.510
and we're going to pay you
quite a lot of money.

00:10:12.510 --> 00:10:15.460
A typical director on the
Fortune 500 company will make

00:10:15.460 --> 00:10:17.770
$100,000 plus a year.

00:10:17.770 --> 00:10:20.330
It's a part-time job.

00:10:20.330 --> 00:10:22.120
We appointed you to keep
an eye on the tools of

00:10:22.120 --> 00:10:22.850
production.

00:10:22.850 --> 00:10:24.470
The problem is the board
of directors aren't

00:10:24.470 --> 00:10:25.180
that good at it either.

00:10:25.180 --> 00:10:27.880
Because it turns out to be
really hard to figure out

00:10:27.880 --> 00:10:30.600
exactly what's going on.

00:10:30.600 --> 00:10:33.240
And this is made worse, because
the members of the

00:10:33.240 --> 00:10:35.560
board of directors are often
chosen by management of the

00:10:35.560 --> 00:10:37.900
company, by the people
running the

00:10:37.900 --> 00:10:39.650
production, not by the owners.

00:10:39.650 --> 00:10:42.190
So they'll make selections of
who's going to be on the board

00:10:42.190 --> 00:10:42.720
of directors.

00:10:42.720 --> 00:10:43.885
And they'll pack it with
their friends who

00:10:43.885 --> 00:10:45.040
will be nice to them.

00:10:45.040 --> 00:10:49.010
So, for example, Richard Grasso
was the CEO of the New

00:10:49.010 --> 00:10:50.610
York Stock Exchange.

00:10:50.610 --> 00:10:53.320
He started out in the mail
room, worked his way up.

00:10:53.320 --> 00:10:55.290
He became CEO of the New York
Stock Exchange and retired

00:10:55.290 --> 00:10:59.120
with $187 million severance
package which was outrageous

00:10:59.120 --> 00:11:01.520
and totally unearned.

00:11:01.520 --> 00:11:03.570
But the board of directors were
a bunch of his buddies

00:11:03.570 --> 00:11:05.070
who'd known him since
he was a kid.

00:11:05.070 --> 00:11:06.250
And they said, he seems
like a nice guy.

00:11:06.250 --> 00:11:08.300
Let's give him a
bunch of money.

00:11:08.300 --> 00:11:09.810
And a lot of the board of
directors, when actually

00:11:09.810 --> 00:11:11.780
grilled on it, didn't actually
know he'd gotten that much.

00:11:11.780 --> 00:11:12.200
They were like, wow.

00:11:12.200 --> 00:11:13.340
We didn't realize
his retirement

00:11:13.340 --> 00:11:14.860
package was that big.

00:11:14.860 --> 00:11:17.610
So it turns out having the board
of directors does not

00:11:17.610 --> 00:11:19.040
solve the agency problem.

00:11:19.040 --> 00:11:21.710
Because there's still too much
of an information imperfection

00:11:21.710 --> 00:11:24.450
between the managers and the
board of directors, not to

00:11:24.450 --> 00:11:27.150
mention the managers
and the owners.

00:11:27.150 --> 00:11:28.170
So what do we do?

00:11:28.170 --> 00:11:29.240
What do we do with this
agency problem?

00:11:29.240 --> 00:11:32.110
Well, this was known
for a lot of years.

00:11:32.110 --> 00:11:37.120
And about 25 years ago, the
thinking was, look, the way to

00:11:37.120 --> 00:11:41.780
solve this problem is we need to
align the incentives of the

00:11:41.780 --> 00:11:43.365
managers and the owners.

00:11:43.365 --> 00:11:45.270
If we're going to solve this
problem, we need to get the

00:11:45.270 --> 00:11:48.480
managers, the producers, to
actually care about maximizing

00:11:48.480 --> 00:11:50.440
profits enough that they'll do
that even if it makes their

00:11:50.440 --> 00:11:52.300
life a little uncomfortable.

00:11:52.300 --> 00:11:53.460
And how do we do that?

00:11:53.460 --> 00:11:56.190
We turn the managers
into owners.

00:11:56.190 --> 00:11:59.150
We give the managers, the
producers, an ownership stake

00:11:59.150 --> 00:12:00.410
in the company.

00:12:00.410 --> 00:12:05.670
We say look, your income is
going to be directly derived

00:12:05.670 --> 00:12:07.620
from the profitability
of this company.

00:12:07.620 --> 00:12:10.100
So now you'll have a direct
incentive to do what's profit

00:12:10.100 --> 00:12:11.470
maximizing even if it makes
your life a little

00:12:11.470 --> 00:12:12.500
uncomfortable.

00:12:12.500 --> 00:12:17.596
Even if it means flying
commercial, you recognize if I

00:12:17.596 --> 00:12:19.530
have my own jet, then
I'm going to suffer.

00:12:19.530 --> 00:12:21.050
So you align the incentives.

00:12:21.050 --> 00:12:22.540
So we want to give
them an ownership

00:12:22.540 --> 00:12:23.270
stake in the company.

00:12:23.270 --> 00:12:24.820
Well, how do you do that?

00:12:24.820 --> 00:12:26.360
How do you give managers
an ownership stake?

00:12:26.360 --> 00:12:28.110
Well, there's two ways
you can do it.

00:12:28.110 --> 00:12:31.460
One way is you can directly
give them stock.

00:12:31.460 --> 00:12:34.840
So you can directly say, look,
instead of paying you in cash,

00:12:34.840 --> 00:12:37.630
we are going to pay you
in company stock.

00:12:37.630 --> 00:12:42.940
So your fortunes will directly
be tied to the performance of

00:12:42.940 --> 00:12:46.180
this company if you
pay them in stock.

00:12:46.180 --> 00:12:49.730
Or, alternatively, you can do
something which turns out to

00:12:49.730 --> 00:12:50.790
be cheaper.

00:12:50.790 --> 00:12:52.200
You can give them
stock options.

00:12:52.200 --> 00:12:54.940
It turns out to be cheaper,
at least, in principle.

00:12:54.940 --> 00:12:56.540
We can give them
stock options.

00:12:56.540 --> 00:12:58.350
So let's talk about what
a stock option is.

00:12:58.350 --> 00:12:59.840
And some of you may deal with
these along the way.

00:13:03.260 --> 00:13:06.210
A stock is a piece of paper
which says you only 0.00001%

00:13:06.210 --> 00:13:07.660
of the company.

00:13:07.660 --> 00:13:10.730
A stock option is simply a piece
of paper which says we

00:13:10.730 --> 00:13:15.610
are granting you the right to
buy the stock at some price.

00:13:15.610 --> 00:13:18.180
Typically, it's today's price.

00:13:18.180 --> 00:13:19.550
We're not giving you a
share of the company.

00:13:19.550 --> 00:13:21.270
You have a piece of paper which
says if the value of

00:13:21.270 --> 00:13:23.900
stock today is $100, you have a
piece of paper which says no

00:13:23.900 --> 00:13:25.400
matter where the stock
ends up, you can

00:13:25.400 --> 00:13:27.540
always buy it for $100.

00:13:27.540 --> 00:13:28.860
Why is that valuable?

00:13:28.860 --> 00:13:33.020
Well, that's valuable because
let's say you give a CEO of a

00:13:33.020 --> 00:13:36.630
company a million options at
$100 each when the price of

00:13:36.630 --> 00:13:38.240
the stock is $100.

00:13:38.240 --> 00:13:42.690
Well, if the price of the stock
rises to $150, that CEO

00:13:42.690 --> 00:13:45.290
can then take his million
options, say, I want to buy

00:13:45.290 --> 00:13:47.400
the shares for 100, which I'm
allowed to by these pieces of

00:13:47.400 --> 00:13:49.800
paper, and I'll turn around
and sell them for $150.

00:13:49.800 --> 00:13:52.250
I've just made $50 million.

00:13:52.250 --> 00:13:55.110
So a stock option is valuable
if the stock goes up.

00:13:55.110 --> 00:13:58.180
But it's worthless if
the stock goes down.

00:13:58.180 --> 00:13:59.980
So it's kind of the ultimate
incentive, if

00:13:59.980 --> 00:14:00.440
you think about it.

00:14:00.440 --> 00:14:03.890
Because what it says to the CEO
is, look, we're going to

00:14:03.890 --> 00:14:05.240
incent you to do better.

00:14:05.240 --> 00:14:07.190
And you make a lot of money
by doing better.

00:14:07.190 --> 00:14:09.860
But if you do worse, you're
not going to get anything.

00:14:09.860 --> 00:14:12.200
And as myself as the owner
it seems great,

00:14:12.200 --> 00:14:13.380
because it's cheaper.

00:14:13.380 --> 00:14:16.850
Because if the stock goes up,
I share some with the guy.

00:14:16.850 --> 00:14:17.500
But I don't care.

00:14:17.500 --> 00:14:17.860
I'm happy.

00:14:17.860 --> 00:14:18.850
The stock goes up.

00:14:18.850 --> 00:14:20.880
If it goes down, I don't have
to give him anything.

00:14:20.880 --> 00:14:23.940
And, in fact, giving someone
a stock option costs,

00:14:23.940 --> 00:14:27.060
effectively, about half as much
as giving them stock.

00:14:27.060 --> 00:14:30.350
So if I say today's stock price,
if I instead of giving

00:14:30.350 --> 00:14:32.170
you a share of stock, I give you
an option to buy a share

00:14:32.170 --> 00:14:35.520
of stock at today's price, the
value to that, what it costs

00:14:35.520 --> 00:14:36.930
me in the market is about half
of what it costs when I

00:14:36.930 --> 00:14:38.670
actually give you the
share of stock.

00:14:38.670 --> 00:14:40.210
So it seems like
the best deal.

00:14:40.210 --> 00:14:42.700
You get all the incentives for
them to raise the price, but

00:14:42.700 --> 00:14:45.240
it costs you half as much.

00:14:45.240 --> 00:14:48.330
And, in fact, there's been
tremendous growth in use of

00:14:48.330 --> 00:14:49.890
stock and stock options.

00:14:49.890 --> 00:14:55.810
So if you look at Figure 12-1,
now, this sort of changes.

00:14:55.810 --> 00:14:59.610
Before 1992, there's only
two categories.

00:14:59.610 --> 00:15:01.250
And after '92, there's three.

00:15:01.250 --> 00:15:06.750
So before '92, we just have to
divide into salary and bonus

00:15:06.750 --> 00:15:08.170
versus options.

00:15:08.170 --> 00:15:11.970
So you see there was essentially
no options in '84.

00:15:11.970 --> 00:15:13.690
This is the mean CEO pay.

00:15:13.690 --> 00:15:16.970
So the typical CEO in 1984 made
$500,000, and it was all

00:15:16.970 --> 00:15:19.220
cash, all salary and bonus.

00:15:19.220 --> 00:15:23.585
By 1992, they made about $1
million, and a decent share of

00:15:23.585 --> 00:15:25.520
it started to be
stock options.

00:15:25.520 --> 00:15:28.000
Now, starting after '92, we
actually break into three

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:31.070
categories which is salary,
bonus, and options.

00:15:31.070 --> 00:15:32.380
But that doesn't
really matter.

00:15:32.380 --> 00:15:34.560
The main thing is to pay
attention to the option share,

00:15:34.560 --> 00:15:36.590
which you see grew
astronomically.

00:15:36.590 --> 00:15:41.000
And so by its peak, in about
2002, first of all, the

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:43.070
typical CEO was making
$3.5 million.

00:15:45.620 --> 00:15:50.360
Second of all, the majority of
that was in stock options.

00:15:50.360 --> 00:15:52.840
In fact, if you look at salary
and bonus, it didn't grow that

00:15:52.840 --> 00:15:55.370
much over time.

00:15:55.370 --> 00:15:59.660
If you look at 1992 versus 2002,
over that decade, salary

00:15:59.660 --> 00:16:03.650
and bonus barely grew, but
options went through the roof.

00:16:03.650 --> 00:16:06.660
So there's a huge increase
in use of these.

00:16:06.660 --> 00:16:10.910
And the motivation is pretty
basic economic intuition.

00:16:10.910 --> 00:16:14.420
What we're going to do is this
is a cheap way to align the

00:16:14.420 --> 00:16:16.665
incentives of owners
and managers.

00:16:19.490 --> 00:16:20.790
And that was why
they took off.

00:16:20.790 --> 00:16:21.880
And everyone thought
it was great.

00:16:21.880 --> 00:16:23.800
And people like Michael Jensen
at Harvard Business School

00:16:23.800 --> 00:16:25.890
made fortunes off having
suggested this, et cetera.

00:16:25.890 --> 00:16:27.460
It was like we solved
the problem.

00:16:27.460 --> 00:16:31.620
And, remember, we did pretty
damn well in the 1990s.

00:16:31.620 --> 00:16:34.380
And a lot of it, people
attributed it to exactly

00:16:34.380 --> 00:16:35.500
what's in this graph.

00:16:35.500 --> 00:16:38.940
That by finally figuring out how
to align the incentives of

00:16:38.940 --> 00:16:41.980
producers and owners, we'd
figured out a way to change

00:16:41.980 --> 00:16:42.820
the economy.

00:16:42.820 --> 00:16:46.540
And people thought we sort of
entered this new economic era

00:16:46.540 --> 00:16:49.070
of massive productivity.

00:16:49.070 --> 00:16:52.390
Well people, as we know
now, were wrong.

00:16:52.390 --> 00:16:54.630
Things slowed down in the
2000s and then now have

00:16:54.630 --> 00:16:57.020
completely crashed.

00:16:57.020 --> 00:16:58.100
And why were they wrong?

00:16:58.100 --> 00:17:01.270
Well, they're wrong because what
makes economics fun is

00:17:01.270 --> 00:17:03.310
unintended consequences.

00:17:03.310 --> 00:17:07.430
And these stock options had
two kinds of unintended

00:17:07.430 --> 00:17:09.569
consequences.

00:17:09.569 --> 00:17:12.869
The first unintended consequence
is that they lead

00:17:12.869 --> 00:17:14.119
to excessive gambling.

00:17:25.200 --> 00:17:29.660
And what I mean by that is that
once your stock option is

00:17:29.660 --> 00:17:32.220
out of the money, once, if
you've got it for 100,

00:17:32.220 --> 00:17:33.390
you're below 100.

00:17:33.390 --> 00:17:35.740
You don't care how
low it goes.

00:17:35.740 --> 00:17:39.020
If you're at 99 or 20,
you don't care.

00:17:39.020 --> 00:17:41.630
All we care about is being
100 verses above.

00:17:41.630 --> 00:17:45.410
What that means is as an owner,
as a manager, you'll

00:17:45.410 --> 00:17:48.890
take excessive risks to go into
the positive territory.

00:17:48.890 --> 00:17:50.600
Even if there's a huge
risk you'll get

00:17:50.600 --> 00:17:51.850
nailed on the downside.

00:17:54.500 --> 00:17:59.170
Contrast to guys working
for a company that's

00:17:59.170 --> 00:18:01.616
currently worth $100.

00:18:01.616 --> 00:18:09.530
One is given stock, and one is
given stock options at $100.

00:18:09.530 --> 00:18:12.060
Imagine they're both going to
leave the company in one year.

00:18:12.060 --> 00:18:13.910
Because there's dynamics with
the long run issues.

00:18:13.910 --> 00:18:14.880
Let's put that aside.

00:18:14.880 --> 00:18:16.580
They're both going to
leave in one year.

00:18:16.580 --> 00:18:19.720
One today is given a share of
stock, and one today is given

00:18:19.720 --> 00:18:21.810
an option to buy at $100.

00:18:21.810 --> 00:18:25.090
And then they're given the
choice of a risky investment.

00:18:25.090 --> 00:18:26.130
Someone comes to them
and says, have I

00:18:26.130 --> 00:18:27.880
got a deal for you.

00:18:27.880 --> 00:18:31.140
I've got an investment that
has a 10% chance it will

00:18:31.140 --> 00:18:34.860
double the value of your company
and a 90% chance the

00:18:34.860 --> 00:18:39.060
value of your company
will fall by 20%.

00:18:39.060 --> 00:18:51.040
So there's a 10% chance of a
100% return and a 90% chance

00:18:51.040 --> 00:18:55.510
of a 20% decline in your
company's value.

00:18:55.510 --> 00:18:57.910
Now, what is the profit
maximizing thing

00:18:57.910 --> 00:18:59.190
to do in this situation?

00:18:59.190 --> 00:19:02.800
Well, to do that, we have to
consider the concept of what

00:19:02.800 --> 00:19:05.375
delivers the company the
highest expected value.

00:19:08.730 --> 00:19:10.850
Expected value is a concept
we'll use-- and we'll come

00:19:10.850 --> 00:19:12.910
back to this later when we
talk about uncertainty--

00:19:12.910 --> 00:19:15.770
it's a concept we use to measure
how you value things

00:19:15.770 --> 00:19:17.130
when there's uncertainty.

00:19:17.130 --> 00:19:20.980
So the expected value of a
gamble is the probability that

00:19:20.980 --> 00:19:27.470
you win times the value if you
win plus the probability that

00:19:27.470 --> 00:19:32.320
you lose times the value
if you lose.

00:19:32.320 --> 00:19:35.570
That's the expected
value of a gamble.

00:19:35.570 --> 00:19:38.210
And the profit maximizing thing
to do would be to take

00:19:38.210 --> 00:19:42.200
gambles of expected values
of greater than zero.

00:19:42.200 --> 00:19:45.460
The expected value is
the summation of the

00:19:45.460 --> 00:19:47.480
value of that gamble.

00:19:47.480 --> 00:19:54.170
This gamble has an expected
value of 0.1 times 100--

00:19:54.170 --> 00:19:56.650
100% return and a 10% chance--

00:19:56.650 --> 00:20:01.590
plus 0.9 times negative 20--

00:20:01.590 --> 00:20:06.790
a 90% of losing 20-- or an
expected value of minus 8%.

00:20:06.790 --> 00:20:09.060
That is if you take this gamble,
and you took it an

00:20:09.060 --> 00:20:11.450
infinite number of times,
you would end up

00:20:11.450 --> 00:20:14.110
losing 8% on average.

00:20:14.110 --> 00:20:15.710
Any one time might work out.

00:20:15.710 --> 00:20:17.340
But by the law of large numbers,
if we took this

00:20:17.340 --> 00:20:20.530
enough times, you'd lose
8% on average.

00:20:20.530 --> 00:20:22.800
So you will lower the value
of your company.

00:20:22.800 --> 00:20:26.840
You will reduce profits
by taking this gamble.

00:20:26.840 --> 00:20:28.300
Your company is worse off
if you take this gamble.

00:20:28.300 --> 00:20:31.810
Well, what would the person who
got the $100 in stocks do?

00:20:31.810 --> 00:20:33.640
They won't take the gamble.

00:20:33.640 --> 00:20:37.310
Because their $100 in stock will
be worth, on average, 8%

00:20:37.310 --> 00:20:38.390
less if they take this gamble.

00:20:38.390 --> 00:20:39.590
So I'm not taking the gamble.

00:20:39.590 --> 00:20:41.000
This is stupid.

00:20:41.000 --> 00:20:43.210
But now let's look at the
guy who got the option.

00:20:43.210 --> 00:20:44.830
His gamble is a little
bit different.

00:20:44.830 --> 00:20:47.496
Because he doesn't care whether
the value of the

00:20:47.496 --> 00:20:49.410
company is 99 or 80.

00:20:49.410 --> 00:20:51.370
He just cares about how much
it goes above 100.

00:20:51.370 --> 00:20:53.400
So what is his calculation?

00:20:53.400 --> 00:20:57.600
Well, his calculation is he
has a 10% chance of making

00:20:57.600 --> 00:21:03.910
100% and a 90% chance of what?

00:21:03.910 --> 00:21:06.880
Zero, ending up with zero.

00:21:06.880 --> 00:21:09.030
He can't lose.

00:21:09.030 --> 00:21:10.740
He has a 90% chance of zero.

00:21:10.740 --> 00:21:12.350
So what is his calculation?

00:21:12.350 --> 00:21:16.250
Well, he uses the positive
10% gamble.

00:21:16.250 --> 00:21:20.135
He makes money on this gamble,
because head he wins, tails he

00:21:20.135 --> 00:21:21.590
walks away.

00:21:21.590 --> 00:21:24.550
The guy who owns the stock loses
if it's tails with this

00:21:24.550 --> 00:21:28.550
weighted coin that only hits
heads 10% of the time.

00:21:28.550 --> 00:21:30.260
This guy only wins.

00:21:30.260 --> 00:21:31.250
So he says, sure.

00:21:31.250 --> 00:21:34.330
Any gamble which has a huge
upside, I'm going to take.

00:21:34.330 --> 00:21:38.500
Because I get all the upside,
and I don't bear the downside.

00:21:38.500 --> 00:21:41.070
So what this does is it leads
to excessive gambling,

00:21:41.070 --> 00:21:41.990
excessive risk taking.

00:21:41.990 --> 00:21:44.910
And that's exactly what we saw
in economy, was companies

00:21:44.910 --> 00:21:48.820
gambling on things which sounded
very good, managers

00:21:48.820 --> 00:21:50.970
gambling on things which sounded
very good, some of

00:21:50.970 --> 00:21:54.890
which worked out very well
and some of which didn't.

00:21:54.890 --> 00:21:56.660
And that's the first problem
we have with the

00:21:56.660 --> 00:21:58.300
use of stock options.

00:21:58.300 --> 00:22:01.690
And questions about that?

00:22:01.690 --> 00:22:01.900
Yeah.

00:22:01.900 --> 00:22:04.876
AUDIENCE: What about using a
package of options like a

00:22:04.876 --> 00:22:07.356
number of stock options
[INAUDIBLE PHRASE]

00:22:10.332 --> 00:22:13.320
package of stock options
[INAUDIBLE PHRASE].

00:22:13.320 --> 00:22:15.290
PROFESSOR: Certainly there are
more sophisticated ways you

00:22:15.290 --> 00:22:16.260
can do that.

00:22:16.260 --> 00:22:17.710
I mean, there's certainly
more sophisticated

00:22:17.710 --> 00:22:18.600
ways you can do that.

00:22:18.600 --> 00:22:22.180
But that's a great segue to the
second problem with these.

00:22:22.180 --> 00:22:25.500
The second problem is who
decided the structure of the

00:22:25.500 --> 00:22:26.950
stock options?

00:22:26.950 --> 00:22:28.600
The managers.

00:22:28.600 --> 00:22:32.060
So the managers had executive
compensation committees that

00:22:32.060 --> 00:22:34.830
designed the stock options
the managers got.

00:22:34.830 --> 00:22:36.360
So the second problem
was there was

00:22:36.360 --> 00:22:39.460
just outright cheating.

00:22:39.460 --> 00:22:41.670
So what you just described would
be a great structure

00:22:41.670 --> 00:22:43.700
which would incentivize them
maximally, but it would not

00:22:43.700 --> 00:22:45.470
make them the most money.

00:22:45.470 --> 00:22:47.690
So the second problem we had
was outright cheating.

00:22:47.690 --> 00:22:49.470
So there's a wonderful
investigation by the Wall

00:22:49.470 --> 00:22:51.850
Street Journal that investigated
a whole list of

00:22:51.850 --> 00:22:53.540
stock option arrangements.

00:22:53.540 --> 00:22:56.470
And what they found was
companies would frequently do

00:22:56.470 --> 00:22:59.140
what's called backdating
stock options.

00:22:59.140 --> 00:23:01.363
What they'd say is, look, the
value of the company just went

00:23:01.363 --> 00:23:04.570
up from $100 to $15 last week.

00:23:04.570 --> 00:23:06.240
We're going to give you
an option at $100.

00:23:06.240 --> 00:23:07.990
And let's pretend it was issued
before the company

00:23:07.990 --> 00:23:08.980
value went up.

00:23:08.980 --> 00:23:11.400
We've just given you money.

00:23:11.400 --> 00:23:13.360
You haven't done anything
to earn that.

00:23:13.360 --> 00:23:14.700
We've just given you money.

00:23:14.700 --> 00:23:18.480
And the Wall Street Journal
found incredible evidence of

00:23:18.480 --> 00:23:20.040
backdating stock options.

00:23:20.040 --> 00:23:21.910
So they had one CEO.

00:23:21.910 --> 00:23:25.886
They Yeah, I'm sorry.

