PROFESSOR: No.

00:23:38.230 --> 00:23:39.270
But here's the thing.

00:23:39.270 --> 00:23:42.460
When I gave it to you, then,
basically, I gave you

00:23:42.460 --> 00:23:43.260
something of value.

00:23:43.260 --> 00:23:45.050
I have to pay for that
thing of value.

00:23:45.050 --> 00:23:46.010
Now, ultimately,
the transaction

00:23:46.010 --> 00:23:47.250
happens in the market.

00:23:47.250 --> 00:23:50.600
But, basically, in other words,
I give you this option

00:23:50.600 --> 00:23:52.390
to buy the stock at $100.

00:23:52.390 --> 00:23:53.840
This is an important point that
I wasn't clear enough on.

00:23:53.840 --> 00:23:56.230
I give you an option to
buy a stock at $100.

00:23:56.230 --> 00:23:58.750
The stock is now worth $150.

00:23:58.750 --> 00:24:02.440
That means that stock I could
have had at $150 as an owner.

00:24:02.440 --> 00:24:02.830
And it's worth $150.

00:24:02.830 --> 00:24:08.530
But by letting you take it at
$100, I let you keep the extra

00:24:08.530 --> 00:24:09.810
$50 instead of me getting it.

00:24:09.810 --> 00:24:12.620
I have a share of stock
which [INAUDIBLE]

00:24:12.620 --> 00:24:16.000
$150.

00:24:16.000 --> 00:24:18.290
I've given that to you.

00:24:18.290 --> 00:24:21.248
I've, essentially, transferred
to you $150.

00:24:21.248 --> 00:24:23.638
AUDIENCE: So when companies
[INAUDIBLE PHRASE].

00:24:28.900 --> 00:24:30.700
PROFESSOR: They'll keep
some amount of shares.

00:24:33.910 --> 00:24:36.450
The owners, they
will sell stock

00:24:36.450 --> 00:24:37.430
and they'll do offerings.

00:24:37.430 --> 00:24:39.070
But the owners own the majority
of the stock.

00:24:39.070 --> 00:24:40.450
That's what makes
them the owners.

00:24:40.450 --> 00:24:42.250
Maybe that's the right
way to put it.

00:24:42.250 --> 00:24:43.500
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE PHRASE].

00:24:48.310 --> 00:24:48.530
PROFESSOR: No.

00:24:48.530 --> 00:24:52.810
Well, in principle, the board
of directors approves stock.

00:24:52.810 --> 00:24:53.510
They don't decide.

00:24:53.510 --> 00:24:55.520
An executive management
committee decides.

00:24:55.520 --> 00:24:57.240
The executive management
committee consists of all the

00:24:57.240 --> 00:24:59.162
golf buddies of the CEO.

00:24:59.162 --> 00:25:00.090
They decide.

00:25:00.090 --> 00:25:01.770
The board of directors is
supposed to make sure nothing

00:25:01.770 --> 00:25:03.055
untoward happens.

00:25:03.055 --> 00:25:05.720
The board of directors, they're
just a bunch of

00:25:05.720 --> 00:25:07.390
retired former executives
who are also golf

00:25:07.390 --> 00:25:09.030
buddies of the manager.

00:25:09.030 --> 00:25:11.580
So they don't really
get it right.

00:25:11.580 --> 00:25:12.820
So there's outright cheating.

00:25:12.820 --> 00:25:17.310
So, for instance, one CEO,
he got six stock options.

00:25:17.310 --> 00:25:21.870
Each one happened to be issued,
happened to be issued

00:25:21.870 --> 00:25:24.040
the day before-- at least on
paper-- was issued the day

00:25:24.040 --> 00:25:26.900
before a huge increase
in the stock price.

00:25:26.900 --> 00:25:28.655
Now, the CEO said he
was just lucky.

00:25:28.655 --> 00:25:31.030
But the Wall Street Journal
did a simulation and

00:25:31.030 --> 00:25:33.080
calculated that there's a 1 in
1 billion chance he could've

00:25:33.080 --> 00:25:34.400
been that lucky.

00:25:34.400 --> 00:25:36.350
That, in fact, what clearly
happened was he got the stock

00:25:36.350 --> 00:25:39.040
options later, and they were
backdated to make it seem like

00:25:39.040 --> 00:25:40.980
he got them before the
price went up.

00:25:40.980 --> 00:25:42.610
But that's not the
best example.

00:25:42.610 --> 00:25:44.990
The best example
is Cablevision.

00:25:44.990 --> 00:25:47.670
They granted and backdated
options to their vice chairman

00:25:47.670 --> 00:25:49.080
from 1997 to 2002.

00:25:49.080 --> 00:25:52.010
So from 1997 to 2002, they gave
them options and they

00:25:52.010 --> 00:25:54.780
kept backdating them to
make them look good.

00:25:54.780 --> 00:25:58.870
The only problem was that
he died in 1999.

00:25:58.870 --> 00:26:01.380
So, basically, they were just
giving money away to this

00:26:01.380 --> 00:26:02.000
guy's heirs.

00:26:02.000 --> 00:26:04.350
Clearly they weren't
incentivizing his performance.

00:26:04.350 --> 00:26:07.400
As the quote said, trying to
incentivize a corpse suggests

00:26:07.400 --> 00:26:09.650
they were not complying with
the spirit of shareholder

00:26:09.650 --> 00:26:11.840
approved stock option plans.

00:26:11.840 --> 00:26:13.740
They were just giving money to
his heirs, because they felt

00:26:13.740 --> 00:26:15.760
bad for him, because they
weren't keeping their yacht up

00:26:15.760 --> 00:26:17.360
or whatever.

00:26:17.360 --> 00:26:20.520
So, basically, this is an
example of a kind of cheating.

00:26:20.520 --> 00:26:21.850
Of course, then you can
go further, and

00:26:21.850 --> 00:26:24.030
there's outright fraud.

00:26:24.030 --> 00:26:25.810
The backdating is sort
of cheating.

00:26:25.810 --> 00:26:26.750
You can go even further.

00:26:26.750 --> 00:26:30.860
I don't know what determines
fraud versus cheating.

00:26:30.860 --> 00:26:33.050
You can just do what
Enron did.

00:26:33.050 --> 00:26:35.040
What Enron did is the executives
there just lied

00:26:35.040 --> 00:26:36.590
about how much money
they were making.

00:26:36.590 --> 00:26:39.100
They just went public with
figures that were wrong.

00:26:39.100 --> 00:26:40.710
The stock price went up.

00:26:40.710 --> 00:26:44.480
They cashed in their
options and quit.

00:26:44.480 --> 00:26:47.410
And as long as you don't get
caught, that's a great deal.

00:26:47.410 --> 00:26:50.580
And if you do get caught, well,
they fine you for 1/3 of

00:26:50.580 --> 00:26:51.640
what you made.

00:26:51.640 --> 00:26:53.080
So who cares?

00:26:53.080 --> 00:26:54.950
So basically it was
outright fraud.

00:26:54.950 --> 00:26:56.630
And this was a lot
of what happened.

00:26:56.630 --> 00:26:58.280
A lot of the wealth that we
thought was created in the

00:26:58.280 --> 00:27:01.200
1990s in the stock market was
really just false wealth

00:27:01.200 --> 00:27:03.160
created by people saying their
company's were worth more than

00:27:03.160 --> 00:27:04.190
they actually were.

00:27:04.190 --> 00:27:05.006
Yeah.

00:27:05.006 --> 00:27:07.386
AUDIENCE: Who decides the salary
[INAUDIBLE PHRASE].

00:27:12.370 --> 00:27:13.690
PROFESSOR: No.

00:27:13.690 --> 00:27:16.010
I mean, once again, it varies
by company to company.

00:27:16.010 --> 00:27:19.260
But, basically, the dividend
payout would be something that

00:27:19.260 --> 00:27:22.110
a different set of managers
would decide, once again,

00:27:22.110 --> 00:27:24.410
subject to approval
of the owners.

00:27:24.410 --> 00:27:27.710
But, once again, the point is
that the owners of a company,

00:27:27.710 --> 00:27:29.880
of a big company, are just a
diffuse set of people who

00:27:29.880 --> 00:27:32.570
don't know what they're doing.

00:27:32.570 --> 00:27:34.790
The managers know exactly
what they're doing.

00:27:34.790 --> 00:27:37.580
The board of directors is in
between and is half clueless,

00:27:37.580 --> 00:27:38.960
half knows what it's doing.

00:27:38.960 --> 00:27:42.390
And that's what leads to
the agency problem.

00:27:42.390 --> 00:27:44.920
What's so interesting about
this example is it sort of

00:27:44.920 --> 00:27:48.160
points out, like in many things
in economics, why we're

00:27:48.160 --> 00:27:49.630
called the dismal science.

00:27:49.630 --> 00:27:52.070
There is no right answer here.

00:27:52.070 --> 00:27:55.340
On the one hand, if you don't
incentivize your owners, then

00:27:55.340 --> 00:27:57.500
they might not do what's
profit maximizing.

00:27:57.500 --> 00:28:00.000
On the other hand, if they
incentivize your owners, they

00:28:00.000 --> 00:28:02.735
might do cheating to maximize
their profits as opposed to

00:28:02.735 --> 00:28:03.640
the company's profits.

00:28:03.640 --> 00:28:05.390
And that's why you need
complicated structures, the

00:28:05.390 --> 00:28:07.050
type that was suggested
in the back.

00:28:07.050 --> 00:28:09.480
And that's why, for example,
they find that companies with

00:28:09.480 --> 00:28:11.760
much more concentrated
ownership, the ones that

00:28:11.760 --> 00:28:14.795
Warren Buffett owns 20% of, they
do a much better job in

00:28:14.795 --> 00:28:17.110
their CEO compensation than
the ones where it's just a

00:28:17.110 --> 00:28:20.480
bunch of people owning
a tiny, tiny percent.

00:28:20.480 --> 00:28:25.460
So that's exactly the kind of
difficulty you face in setting

00:28:25.460 --> 00:28:27.380
up executive compensation.

00:28:27.380 --> 00:28:30.610
Now, this was a real departure
from the kind of things we

00:28:30.610 --> 00:28:32.830
talked about, just
one example.

00:28:32.830 --> 00:28:34.410
Partly what we want to do in
this course, I want to teach

00:28:34.410 --> 00:28:35.300
you about basic economics.

00:28:35.300 --> 00:28:37.450
I partly want to excite you
about what else you can go on

00:28:37.450 --> 00:28:39.390
and do in economics.

00:28:39.390 --> 00:28:41.820
What I've just done in the last
half hour is a microcosm

00:28:41.820 --> 00:28:44.320
of the field of corporate
finance.

00:28:44.320 --> 00:28:45.350
There's an entire field
in economics

00:28:45.350 --> 00:28:46.100
called corporate finance.

00:28:46.100 --> 00:28:47.890
We teach it in course 15.

00:28:47.890 --> 00:28:48.950
And it's a terrific course.

