about this kind of more
interesting tweaks

00:29:35.830 --> 00:29:37.930
and what we do here.

00:29:37.930 --> 00:29:41.590
And other questions about
this before I move on?

00:29:41.590 --> 00:29:43.250
OK.

00:29:43.250 --> 00:29:46.840
Now we're going to stop with
that topic, and we're going to

00:29:46.840 --> 00:29:51.380
move to sort of an
in between topic.

00:29:51.380 --> 00:29:54.760
That is, we've been talking
about firms and firm profit

00:29:54.760 --> 00:29:55.870
maximization.

00:29:55.870 --> 00:29:57.660
And we talked about how that
depends on the structure of

00:29:57.660 --> 00:30:00.030
the market and perfect
competition.

00:30:00.030 --> 00:30:03.370
Starting in two lectures, we're
going to start talking

00:30:03.370 --> 00:30:05.170
about alternative market
structures like

00:30:05.170 --> 00:30:07.240
monopoly and oligopoly.

00:30:07.240 --> 00:30:10.550
But in order to talk about them,
we need to introduce a

00:30:10.550 --> 00:30:12.670
new concept we haven't
used before.

00:30:12.670 --> 00:30:13.560
And that's what we'll
do the rest of this

00:30:13.560 --> 00:30:16.010
lecture and next lecture.

00:30:16.010 --> 00:30:19.490
We need to move from positive
economics to normative

00:30:19.490 --> 00:30:27.080
economics, from positive
economics to normative.

00:30:30.670 --> 00:30:35.540
Positive analysis is the study
of the way things are.

00:30:35.540 --> 00:30:37.990
So positive analysis is
explaining why do firms

00:30:37.990 --> 00:30:39.360
produce this many widgets?

00:30:39.360 --> 00:30:41.080
Why do they hire this
many workers?

00:30:41.080 --> 00:30:43.170
Why did I buy this many CDs?

00:30:43.170 --> 00:30:45.050
That's a positive analysis,
trying to explain the way

00:30:45.050 --> 00:30:46.570
things are.

00:30:46.570 --> 00:30:49.150
That's what we've done,
by and large, so far.

00:30:49.150 --> 00:30:52.130
Normative analysis is the
analysis of the way

00:30:52.130 --> 00:30:54.100
things should be.

00:30:54.100 --> 00:30:56.380
Is it good that I bought
that many CDs?

00:30:56.380 --> 00:30:58.690
Is it good that the company
made that much profits?

00:30:58.690 --> 00:31:01.430
Would be better if we have a
minimum wage or don't have a

00:31:01.430 --> 00:31:03.250
minimum wage?

00:31:03.250 --> 00:31:05.110
Normative analysis is the
analysis of the way things

00:31:05.110 --> 00:31:08.690
should be as opposed to
the way they are.

00:31:08.690 --> 00:31:12.780
So, for example, we showed in
the last lecture that in the

00:31:12.780 --> 00:31:16.910
long run, with free entry and
exit, all firms are driven to

00:31:16.910 --> 00:31:20.250
zero profit, and the supply
curve is horizontal.

00:31:20.250 --> 00:31:22.860
Well, is that a good thing?

00:31:22.860 --> 00:31:23.300
We don't know.

00:31:23.300 --> 00:31:24.520
We just said it happened.

00:31:24.520 --> 00:31:25.565
I described why it happened.

00:31:25.565 --> 00:31:26.230
But I didn't tell you
if it was a good

00:31:26.230 --> 00:31:27.710
thing or a bad thing.

00:31:27.710 --> 00:31:30.360
Zero profits, I make a lot of
money off the profits that the

00:31:30.360 --> 00:31:32.800
companies I own make.

00:31:32.800 --> 00:31:35.500
I don't know if I want to
work with zero profits.

00:31:35.500 --> 00:31:36.910
I've got a lot of
stock and stuff.

00:31:36.910 --> 00:31:39.010
And I'm making money because
these companies make profits.

00:31:39.010 --> 00:31:39.975
I don't think I'd
be that happy to

00:31:39.975 --> 00:31:41.000
work with zero profits.

00:31:41.000 --> 00:31:42.110
How do we think about whether
that's a good

00:31:42.110 --> 00:31:43.550
world or a bad world?

00:31:43.550 --> 00:31:46.240
How do we think about whether
we like these outcomes or

00:31:46.240 --> 00:31:48.500
don't like them?

00:31:48.500 --> 00:31:51.635
These are the tools of normative
economics or what we

00:31:51.635 --> 00:31:54.280
will refer to as welfare
economics.

00:31:57.150 --> 00:31:59.010
Now, let me be clear here.

00:31:59.010 --> 00:32:01.330
The term welfare, as you might
have heard it, often refers to

00:32:01.330 --> 00:32:03.040
money you give to low
income populations.

00:32:03.040 --> 00:32:04.250
And we'll talk about that
kind of welfare

00:32:04.250 --> 00:32:05.700
later in the semester.

00:32:05.700 --> 00:32:08.020
Here, when I say welfare,
I mean well-being.

00:32:08.020 --> 00:32:10.350
Welfare is the term economists
use as the measure of

00:32:10.350 --> 00:32:12.080
well-being.

00:32:12.080 --> 00:32:15.330
We need to start talking about
welfare economics, measuring

00:32:15.330 --> 00:32:19.170
the impact of economic outcomes
on well-being, not

00:32:19.170 --> 00:32:22.540
just studying what happens when
firms maximize profits or

00:32:22.540 --> 00:32:26.180
consumers maximize utility,
but measuring how we feel

00:32:26.180 --> 00:32:30.760
about it, measuring whether
it's good or bad, and

00:32:30.760 --> 00:32:32.460
measuring whether some
outcomes might be

00:32:32.460 --> 00:32:33.240
preferred to others.

00:32:33.240 --> 00:32:36.190
Because if we don't do that, we
can't ever talk about the

00:32:36.190 --> 00:32:38.380
role of the government
in the economy.

00:32:38.380 --> 00:32:41.480
Until you start talking about
welfare, you can't talk about

00:32:41.480 --> 00:32:42.330
whether we should
have government

00:32:42.330 --> 00:32:44.310
interventions or not.

00:32:44.310 --> 00:32:45.960
You can only talk about
what happens, not

00:32:45.960 --> 00:32:48.160
whether it should happen.

00:32:48.160 --> 00:32:51.210
Now, the problem of welfare
economics is that it's a lot

00:32:51.210 --> 00:32:53.670
harder because of something
I mentioned when we

00:32:53.670 --> 00:32:55.550
talked about utility.

00:32:55.550 --> 00:33:00.200
Utility is an ordinal concept,
not a cardinal concept.

00:33:00.200 --> 00:33:01.950
Utility is an ordinal concept,
not a cardinal concept.

00:33:01.950 --> 00:33:04.660
That is, utils are
meaningless.

00:33:04.660 --> 00:33:06.970
We use utility functions to
decide whether you prefer

00:33:06.970 --> 00:33:09.830
package A or package B. But the
actual amount of utils you

00:33:09.830 --> 00:33:14.100
get, unlike profits, is sort
of a meaningless concept.

00:33:14.100 --> 00:33:17.060
It's just sort of an index.

00:33:17.060 --> 00:33:19.500
So what we do to do welfare
economics is we turn from

00:33:19.500 --> 00:33:21.920
utils to dollars.

00:33:21.920 --> 00:33:24.810
We measure welfare in dollars
which is easy on

00:33:24.810 --> 00:33:26.050
the corporate side.

00:33:26.050 --> 00:33:27.520
That's profits.

00:33:27.520 --> 00:33:28.650
How do we do it on the
consumer side?

00:33:28.650 --> 00:33:31.730
We do it through the concept
that we call compensating

00:33:31.730 --> 00:33:38.310
variation, which is one of these
things where economists

00:33:38.310 --> 00:33:40.380
use fancy terms for something
which isn't that hard to

00:33:40.380 --> 00:33:42.530
understand.

00:33:42.530 --> 00:33:44.210
But you need to know the fancy
terms, because that's kind of

00:33:44.210 --> 00:33:46.700
how we teach, compensating
variation.

00:33:46.700 --> 00:33:53.510
That is instead of asking, how
sad are you about outcome x,

00:33:53.510 --> 00:33:56.325
we ask, how many dollars
would it take?

00:33:59.110 --> 00:34:03.590
Instead of asking, how sad would
you be to not have a CD,

00:34:03.590 --> 00:34:06.680
we ask, how much would
you pay to avoid

00:34:06.680 --> 00:34:07.930
being in that situation?

00:34:10.120 --> 00:34:16.920
So instead of asking, how sad
are you that you end up with

00:34:16.920 --> 00:34:20.639
this car instead of that car,
we don't want to measure the

00:34:20.639 --> 00:34:22.980
utils of driving a Hyundai
versus a Lexus.

00:34:22.980 --> 00:34:23.960
We can't measure those.

00:34:23.960 --> 00:34:27.810
What we can ask, is how much
more will you pay to get the

00:34:27.810 --> 00:34:29.730
Lexus than the Hyundai?

00:34:29.730 --> 00:34:33.030
And that's $1 measure
of your utils.

00:34:33.030 --> 00:34:34.260
That's a compensating
variation.

00:34:34.260 --> 00:34:38.010
How much do you have
to be compensated?

00:34:38.010 --> 00:34:41.719
So, in other words, instead of
asking you how sad are you

00:34:41.719 --> 00:34:44.280
that you couldn't get tickets
to a Lady Gaga concert--

00:34:44.280 --> 00:34:46.159
maybe that's not a good example
because no one's sad

00:34:46.159 --> 00:34:46.580
about that.

00:34:46.580 --> 00:34:48.630
But let's say you were.

00:34:48.630 --> 00:34:51.560
Let's say I am because my
daughter wants to see her.

00:34:51.560 --> 00:34:52.650
How sad are you?

00:34:52.650 --> 00:34:56.050
I ask, instead, how much would
you pay to get the tickets to

00:34:56.050 --> 00:34:57.300
the Lady Gaga concert?

00:34:59.630 --> 00:35:01.140
That's a measure of how
sad you were you

00:35:01.140 --> 00:35:02.310
couldn't get them.

00:35:02.310 --> 00:35:05.490
Because you'll pay an amount to
compensate yourself for the

00:35:05.490 --> 00:35:07.040
sadness of not getting them.

00:35:07.040 --> 00:35:10.340
So it's a way of turning
utils into dollars.

00:35:10.340 --> 00:35:12.750
And that leads to the concept
that we'll refer to throughout

00:35:12.750 --> 00:35:14.000
the semester.

00:35:15.760 --> 00:35:18.370
That leads to the concept
of consumer surplus.

00:35:24.890 --> 00:35:30.620
Consumer surplus measures the
benefit that a consumer gets

00:35:30.620 --> 00:35:34.740
from consuming a good above
and beyond what they

00:35:34.740 --> 00:35:36.250
paid for the good.

00:35:36.250 --> 00:35:50.110
So it's the benefit of
consumption beyond the price.

00:35:50.110 --> 00:35:51.770
So your consumer surplus--

00:35:51.770 --> 00:35:53.480
surplus means extra--

00:35:53.480 --> 00:35:56.400
is how much you enjoy consuming
something above and

00:35:56.400 --> 00:35:59.210
beyond what you had
to pay for it.

00:35:59.210 --> 00:36:04.450
In other words, the idea is if
you have to pay exactly as

00:36:04.450 --> 00:36:07.390
much as you'd enjoy the good,
there's no consumer surplus.

00:36:07.390 --> 00:36:08.930
So let's do an example.

00:36:08.930 --> 00:36:13.490
So consider my demand to
buy a Lady Gaga CD.

00:36:13.490 --> 00:36:14.330
I've got to update
my examples.

00:36:14.330 --> 00:36:15.400
You guys don't buy
CDs anymore.

00:36:15.400 --> 00:36:19.680
How many of you have bought
a CD in the last year?

00:36:19.680 --> 00:36:20.822
Wow.

00:36:20.822 --> 00:36:21.950
OK, let me ask another
question,

00:36:21.950 --> 00:36:22.380
just one for the record.

00:36:22.380 --> 00:36:23.980
Just because I have to decide
how hard a time to give my

00:36:23.980 --> 00:36:25.090
16-year-old son.

00:36:25.090 --> 00:36:29.283
How many of you typically
pay when you buy a song?

00:36:29.283 --> 00:36:30.610
Wow.

00:36:30.610 --> 00:36:30.770
OK.

00:36:30.770 --> 00:36:31.200
Let me ask another one.

00:36:31.200 --> 00:36:35.790
How many of you typically don't
pay when you buy a song.

00:36:35.790 --> 00:36:37.730
Well, when you get a song, when
you download a song, you

00:36:37.730 --> 00:36:39.090
know what I mean, when
you download a song.

00:36:39.090 --> 00:36:40.950
So the majority of you don't pay
when you download a song.

00:36:40.950 --> 00:36:41.360
Interesting.

00:36:41.360 --> 00:36:42.610
OK.

00:36:44.900 --> 00:36:46.160
I'll update this next year.

00:36:46.160 --> 00:36:47.440
But, for now, we're still
10 years ago.

00:36:47.440 --> 00:36:49.810
Consider my demand for
Lady Gaga CDs.

00:36:49.810 --> 00:36:53.310
I'm trying to decide whether
to buy the marginal CD.

00:36:53.310 --> 00:36:58.380
And let's say that it's
worth $15 to me.

00:36:58.380 --> 00:37:00.980
I'd be willing to pay $15
for the Lady Gaga CD.

00:37:00.980 --> 00:37:03.890
And let's say the
price is $15.

00:37:03.890 --> 00:37:07.850
In that case, there's
no surplus to me.

00:37:07.850 --> 00:37:08.980
There's nothing extra.

00:37:08.980 --> 00:37:11.005
I've paid what I was
willing to pay.

00:37:11.005 --> 00:37:14.000
So that's a case of a zero
consumer surplus.

00:37:14.000 --> 00:37:16.940
The consumer surplus is how
much extra I got from

00:37:16.940 --> 00:37:17.330
consuming it.

00:37:17.330 --> 00:37:18.085
I've got no extra.

00:37:18.085 --> 00:37:19.460
It was worth $15.

00:37:19.460 --> 00:37:22.850
I paid $15, no surplus.

00:37:22.850 --> 00:37:27.730
Now let's say that the
price was $10.

00:37:27.730 --> 00:37:29.130
Then I've got a surplus.

00:37:29.130 --> 00:37:30.340
I've got $5 in surplus.

00:37:30.340 --> 00:37:32.050
I was willing to pay $15.

00:37:32.050 --> 00:37:36.410
It makes me $15 happier to
have this Lady Gaga CD.

00:37:36.410 --> 00:37:38.170
But I only had to
pay $10 for it.

00:37:38.170 --> 00:37:40.930
So I've derived some surplus.

00:37:40.930 --> 00:37:43.670
Well, how do we know what
people's willingness to pay

00:37:43.670 --> 00:37:46.680
for a good is?

00:37:46.680 --> 00:37:48.320
The demand curve.

00:37:48.320 --> 00:37:50.300
That's the definition
of the demand curve.

00:37:50.300 --> 00:37:53.470
The demand curve measures
your willingness to pay.

00:37:53.470 --> 00:37:55.530
So let's go to the
second figure.

00:37:55.530 --> 00:38:00.300
Think about the demand
curve for CDs.

00:38:00.300 --> 00:38:02.740
There's some demand
curve for CDs.

00:38:02.740 --> 00:38:07.880
What this measures is the
utility maximizing choice.

00:38:07.880 --> 00:38:12.030
Every point in this demand curve
represents my utility

00:38:12.030 --> 00:38:15.240
maximizing choice
at that price.

00:38:18.980 --> 00:38:22.000
This is backwards.

00:38:22.000 --> 00:38:24.830
That should be a $15 on the
y-axis and a $5 on the x-axis,

00:38:24.830 --> 00:38:25.290
Sorry, guys.

00:38:25.290 --> 00:38:29.130
It should be $15 on
the y-axis and a--

00:38:29.130 --> 00:38:29.430
no.

00:38:29.430 --> 00:38:30.030
Wait, hold on one second.

00:38:30.030 --> 00:38:31.280
Time out.

00:38:33.190 --> 00:38:34.910
At $5, I get no consumer
surplus.

00:38:45.072 --> 00:38:46.580
Yeah, this graph is
kind of messed up.

00:38:46.580 --> 00:38:47.830
Let me draw a new one here.

00:38:51.000 --> 00:38:53.270
So you've got my demand
curve for CDs.

00:38:53.270 --> 00:38:54.535
You've got the quantity
and the price.

00:38:57.910 --> 00:39:04.390
And I've got some utility
function that delivers this

00:39:04.390 --> 00:39:05.580
demand curve.

00:39:05.580 --> 00:39:08.210
And let's say the way this
works, this demand curve for

00:39:08.210 --> 00:39:12.290
CDs, let's say the way this
works is that I am

00:39:12.290 --> 00:39:16.280
willing to buy 1 CD.

00:39:16.280 --> 00:39:21.500
I'm willing to buy if the
price is $20, I'm

00:39:21.500 --> 00:39:24.160
willing to buy 1 CD.

00:39:24.160 --> 00:39:28.200
So at a price of $20, I'm
willing to buy 1 CD.

00:39:28.200 --> 00:39:32.290
So if I get that 1 CD at $20,
then basically that's my

00:39:32.290 --> 00:39:33.540
willingness to pay.

00:39:33.540 --> 00:39:36.020
It equals a price, so there's
no consumer surplus.

00:39:36.020 --> 00:39:38.180
Really imagine it's right
next to that y-axis.

00:39:47.280 --> 00:39:52.740
Now let's the price
falls to $15.

00:39:52.740 --> 00:39:53.040
Sorry.

00:39:53.040 --> 00:39:54.100
That's a 1.

00:39:54.100 --> 00:39:54.510
That's the 1.

00:39:54.510 --> 00:39:55.225
That's a 20.

00:39:55.225 --> 00:39:57.340
At a price of $20, I'm
willing to buy 1.

00:39:57.340 --> 00:40:00.290
At a price of $15, I'm
willing to buy 5.

00:40:00.290 --> 00:40:01.540
I'm willing to buy 5 CDs.

00:40:04.440 --> 00:40:06.680
Now, what is my consumer
surplus?

00:40:06.680 --> 00:40:08.030
Well, let's ask.

00:40:08.030 --> 00:40:12.290
For the first CD, I got
no consumer surplus.

00:40:12.290 --> 00:40:17.410
But for the second, I
was willing to pay.

00:40:17.410 --> 00:40:19.120
When the price was $20, I
got no consumer surplus.

00:40:19.120 --> 00:40:21.270
Now let's say the
price is $15.

00:40:21.270 --> 00:40:24.840
So what was I willing to
pay for the first CD?

00:40:24.840 --> 00:40:25.460
$20.

00:40:25.460 --> 00:40:27.363
So what's my consumer surplus
on the first CD?

00:40:27.363 --> 00:40:28.670
5.

00:40:28.670 --> 00:40:32.150
So on that first CD, I got
a consumer surplus of 5.

00:40:32.150 --> 00:40:35.780
The second CD, I was willing to
pay less because I've got

00:40:35.780 --> 00:40:37.160
diminishing marginal utility.

00:40:37.160 --> 00:40:40.190
But I was still willing
to pay more than $15.

00:40:40.190 --> 00:40:42.170
So I've got some
surplus there.

00:40:42.170 --> 00:40:43.790
Third CD here, et cetera.

00:40:43.790 --> 00:40:47.870
But on the fifth CD, I derive
no surplus, because I was

00:40:47.870 --> 00:40:51.535
willing to pay $15 for that
fifth CD, and I paid $15 for

00:40:51.535 --> 00:40:53.080
that fifth CD.

00:40:53.080 --> 00:40:59.500
What that means is that all of
this is my consumer surplus.

00:40:59.500 --> 00:41:05.640
Because on every unit, because
I paid a fixed price of $15,

00:41:05.640 --> 00:41:08.640
and for my fifth CD, that
delivered no surplus, that was

00:41:08.640 --> 00:41:09.330
indifferent.

00:41:09.330 --> 00:41:13.470
But in my first through fourth
CDs, that made me very happy.

00:41:13.470 --> 00:41:16.900
Because I was willing to pay
more than $15 for those.

00:41:16.900 --> 00:41:20.800
So my consumer surplus is the
amount by which I derive

00:41:20.800 --> 00:41:22.740
utility above what
I was willing to

00:41:22.740 --> 00:41:25.400
pay, above the price--

00:41:25.400 --> 00:41:26.580
I'm sorry-- the amount
that I was willing to

00:41:26.580 --> 00:41:28.010
pay about the price.

00:41:28.010 --> 00:41:31.070
The amount I'm willing to pay is
every point on this curve.

00:41:31.070 --> 00:41:36.250
So anything I buy that I was
willing to pay more for the

00:41:36.250 --> 00:41:37.710
price for, I derived
surplus on.

00:41:37.710 --> 00:41:41.670
So this becomes my
consumer surplus.

00:41:41.670 --> 00:41:46.380
So, basically, consumer surplus
is the area under the

00:41:46.380 --> 00:41:50.000
demand curve above the price.

00:41:50.000 --> 00:41:52.810
So, graphically, consumer
surplus is going to be the

00:41:52.810 --> 00:41:56.960
area under the demand curve
above the price.

00:41:56.960 --> 00:41:59.110
Intuitively, why is that?

00:41:59.110 --> 00:42:04.510
Intuitively, what's going on is
that every unit above the

00:42:04.510 --> 00:42:07.110
price under the demand curve
are units which I valued

00:42:07.110 --> 00:42:08.350
higher than the price.

00:42:08.350 --> 00:42:11.310
So I get surplus on them.

00:42:11.310 --> 00:42:12.000
OK.

00:42:12.000 --> 00:42:13.100
Question?

00:42:13.100 --> 00:42:13.957
Yeah.

00:42:13.957 --> 00:42:15.556
AUDIENCE: If you're
[UNINTELLIGIBLE] this, would

00:42:15.556 --> 00:42:17.160
you start at zero?

00:42:17.160 --> 00:42:19.050
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:42:19.050 --> 00:42:21.070
Really, in some sense, you'd
want to start at zero.

00:42:21.070 --> 00:42:22.620
It's really the integral
of this whole area.

00:42:22.620 --> 00:42:23.660
The problem is it's discrete.

00:42:23.660 --> 00:42:26.010
I should have a stepwise
curve here.

00:42:26.010 --> 00:42:26.790
I made it discrete.

00:42:26.790 --> 00:42:30.020
But, really, it's the integral
of this area.

00:42:30.020 --> 00:42:30.743
Yeah.

00:42:30.743 --> 00:42:33.158
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE PHRASE].

00:42:33.158 --> 00:42:34.610
upward sloping demand curve?

00:42:34.610 --> 00:42:34.980
PROFESSOR: I'm sorry.

00:42:34.980 --> 00:42:37.860
AUDIENCE: With an upward
sloping demand curve.

00:42:37.860 --> 00:42:40.690
PROFESSOR: With an upward
sloping demand curve, well, as

00:42:40.690 --> 00:42:42.150
I said, we don't believe
in Giffen goods.

00:42:42.150 --> 00:42:43.870
We think they are a fantasy.

00:42:43.870 --> 00:42:46.650
So with an upward sloping
demand curve,

00:42:46.650 --> 00:42:47.900
how would that work?

00:42:51.700 --> 00:42:56.300
So an upward sloping demand
curve, then that would say

00:42:56.300 --> 00:43:05.500
that if the price is here, then
you'd have an infinite

00:43:05.500 --> 00:43:05.990
consumer surplus.

00:43:05.990 --> 00:43:08.096
It wouldn't be well-defined.

00:43:08.096 --> 00:43:09.590
It wouldn't be well-defined.

00:43:09.590 --> 00:43:10.660
So I don't know how
you'd do that.

00:43:10.660 --> 00:43:13.650
That's why we don't like upward
sloping demand curves.

00:43:13.650 --> 00:43:14.360
Yeah.

00:43:14.360 --> 00:43:14.640
Question?

00:43:14.640 --> 00:43:15.420
No?

00:43:15.420 --> 00:43:15.890
OK.

00:43:15.890 --> 00:43:19.930
So, basically, what you end up
with is this consumer surplus

00:43:19.930 --> 00:43:22.440
concept which, basically, as
pointed out mathematically, is

00:43:22.440 --> 00:43:23.820
the integral of this area.

00:43:23.820 --> 00:43:25.200
But we're not going to
make you integrate.

00:43:25.200 --> 00:43:28.480
It's basically this triangle
which is basically all the

00:43:28.480 --> 00:43:33.010
units above the price, all the
units for which you're willing

00:43:33.010 --> 00:43:34.290
to pay more than the price.

00:43:34.290 --> 00:43:37.990
And you get consumer surplus
on every unit you buy up to

00:43:37.990 --> 00:43:39.420
the point where your
willingness to

00:43:39.420 --> 00:43:41.230
pay equals the price.

00:43:41.230 --> 00:43:44.320
And that's our normative
measure of welfare.

00:43:44.320 --> 00:43:47.660
That's our normative measure
of how happy you are.

00:43:47.660 --> 00:43:49.510
And the key that drives this is

00:43:49.510 --> 00:43:50.370
diminishing marginal utility.

00:43:50.370 --> 00:43:52.540
That's why we don't like upward
sloping demand curves.

00:43:52.540 --> 00:43:55.280
What drives this is diminishing
marginal utility.

00:43:55.280 --> 00:43:57.860
It's that with each additional
unit I'm willing to pay less

00:43:57.860 --> 00:43:59.500
and less for.

00:43:59.500 --> 00:44:01.680
So I'm going to get less and
less surplus off each

00:44:01.680 --> 00:44:03.790
additional unit I buy.

00:44:03.790 --> 00:44:05.560
And that's going to
be the key thing.

00:44:05.560 --> 00:44:08.540
The key intuition that you guys
have to remember is that

00:44:08.540 --> 00:44:12.810
the last unit that I'm willing
to buy at that price, by

00:44:12.810 --> 00:44:21.100
definition, I get no surplus
on, or I get a $0.001 of

00:44:21.100 --> 00:44:22.510
surplus on.

00:44:22.510 --> 00:44:26.520
Because if I've got a lot of
surplus, I'd buy 1 more.

00:44:26.520 --> 00:44:30.670
So, by definition, the marginal
unit is the one where

00:44:30.670 --> 00:44:32.850
surplus is driven to 0.

00:44:32.850 --> 00:44:35.810
And units before that are the
ones with positive surplus.

00:44:35.810 --> 00:44:37.800
And that's why an important
intuition to have is the

00:44:37.800 --> 00:44:40.260
amount of surplus you're going
to get from a purchase is

00:44:40.260 --> 00:44:44.040
going to be about how far away
from the price point you are.

00:44:44.040 --> 00:44:45.680
Those first units are going
to give you more surplus.

00:44:45.680 --> 00:44:48.020
And that's going to dwindle as
you get to the actual last

00:44:48.020 --> 00:44:49.940
unit you buy at that price.

00:44:49.940 --> 00:44:51.860
Any questions about that?

